@robinhanson Big debate in the VC industry right now whether these changes are significant enough to cause long-term systemic change.
@robinhanson Change 3: There are new funding alternatives that didn't used to exist -- seed funds, crowdfunding, AngelList, etc.
@robinhanson Change 2: Some VC firms (e.g. mine) believe we have created new and differentiated ways to actively help our startups succeed.
@robinhanson Change 1: Entrepreneurs are far more networked with one another now vs before; actual VC behavior may now be more important.
@adamgurri @robinhanson Yes, the self-fulfilling part is the key. Self-fulfilling positive feedback loop.
@robinhanson Arguably these dynamics are changing in real time in some interesting ways:
@robinhanson You walk into Sequoia, the walls are covered with posters from Apple, Oracle, Cisco, Google (all Sequoia funded). There it is.
@robinhanson They have an aura of success as a consequence of having previously funded successful startups.
@robinhanson Yes, that's the core positive feedback loop. How it starts is less meaningful than how it perpetuates.
@robinhanson In essence, a new startup uses its VC's brand as a credibility bridge until the startup establishes its own brand.
@robinhanson The startup is engaged in a war for employees, customers, and future investors. Top VC brand halo helps with all three.
@robinhanson Founders care about the VC brand halo because potential employees, potential customers, and other potential investors care.
@robinhanson The main historical driver of positive selection is prior success: a halo branding effect that new startups seek.
@robinhanson The battle among VC firms is less "who is smarter?" than "who do the best founders approach first?".
@robinhanson Core dynamic: A few firms have positive selection on their side; the other firms have adverse selection working against them.
